1) Problem Statement & Context¶

Childhood malnutrition is a global public health challenge. Children who are malnourished are not able to grow up to their full potential as it hampers their physical and mental growth. Malnutrition is classified into three indicators; stunting, wasting and underweight. Each of these three indicators reflect the childs growth trajectory as compared to the standards defined by the World Health Organization.

We aim to explore the determinants of childhood malnutrition in the United States. In particular, we want to study the factors that are associated with a childs development indicators before and after birth. These factors can include but are not limited to the mothers health, antenatal and postnatal care, dietary patterns of the mother and child, access to clean water, sanitation and hygiene, household income and other household demographics.

Data Description¶

The dataset is the de-identified information on births and infant deaths in Indiana state between 2010 and 2019. Each row is indexed by a de-identified unique ID for each mother and another unique ID for each child. (Link: https://hub.mph.in.gov/dataset/indiana-births-and-infant-deaths)

There are a total of 19 features with 813,837 rows. The following table on the next page shows the title of each feature/column, description of each feature, and range of possible values.

2-1) Dataset Cleaning & Preliminary Explorations¶

In the interest of time and running the analysis in a timely fashion, only 50% of the data was used by randomly sampling 50% of the data with a random_state of 1. For each question, undersampling was performed such that there was a 50-50 ratio between the labels for the respective classification variables.¶

Model 1: Decision Tree¶

Model Tuning of Multiple Hyperparameters¶

With reasonable ranges defined, Grid Search CV was done to the model to find perform model tuning and find the best set of hyperparamters to use for the model

In [18]:
# Define model to use for grid search cv
dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)
# Define values to try for each hyperparameter of random forest classifier to be used in grid search cv
params = {'max_leaf_nodes': range(2, 50),
          'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
          'max_depth': range(1, 20, 1)}
# Define Grid Search CV model
dtc_gs_cv = GridSearchCV(dtc,
                     param_grid=params,
                     scoring='accuracy',
                     cv=10)
# Fit grid search cv model to training data
dtc_gs_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Print best params
print(dtc_gs_cv.best_params_)

{'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': 6, 'max_leaf_nodes': 21}

The best hyperparameters found for Decision Tree seems to be one with the max depth of 6, max leaf nodes of 21, and a splitting criterion using the gini method. Using these hyperparameters, a final tuned model is trained on the entire traning set and tested for final performance metric

Tuned Decision Tree Performance Metrics & Feature Importance¶

Model Tuning of Multiple Hyperparameters¶

With reasonable ranges defined, Grid Search CV was done to the model to find perform model tuning and find the best set of hyperparamters to use for the model

In [24]:

rfc = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1)

          'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
          'max_depth': range(1, 10, 1)}

                     param_grid=params,
                     scoring='accuracy',
                     cv=10)

rfc_gs_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Print best params
print(rfc_gs_cv.best_params_)

{'criterion': 'entropy', 'max_depth': 6, 'n_estimators': 120}

The best hyperparameters found for Decision Tree seems to be one with 120 trees (estimators) with max depth of 6, and a splitting criterion using the entropy method. Using these hyperparameters, a final tuned model is trained on the entire traning set and tested for final performance metric

Tuned Random Forest Performance Metrics & Feature Importance¶

Model Tuning¶

In [27]:
knn_cv_errors = []
for i in range(1,50):
    knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i)
    cv_error = np.mean(cross_val_score(knn_model, X_train, y_train, cv=10))
    knn_cv_errors.append(cv_error)

max_score = np.nanmax(knn_cv_errors)
max_ind = np.nanargmax(knn_cv_errors) + 1
print("Highest CV Accuracy: ", max_score)
print("Number of Neighbors for Lowest CV Error: ", max_ind)
x_graph = list(range(1,50))
plt.plot(x_graph,knn_cv_errors)
plt.xlabel("Number of Neighbors (k)")
plt.ylabel("CV Error")
plt.axvline(max_ind,color="red")
plt.show()

Number of Neighbors for Lowest CV Error:  45

Model Performance & Selection¶

In [31]:
# Show plot of ROC curves
plt.plot(dtc_fpr, dtc_tpr, label = 'Decision Tree')
plt.plot(rfc_fpr, rfc_tpr, label = 'Random Forest')
plt.plot(knn_fpr, knn_tpr, label = 'KNN')
plt.xlabel('FPR')
plt.ylabel('TPR')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

The performance of each model was as follows: Decision Tree had an accuracy of 65.8%, while Random Forest had an accuracy of 65.7%, and KNN with an accruacy of 63.0% for the test data. Although the decision tree had the highest overall testing accuracy, the ROC curve that shows the rate of True Positives and False Positives indicates that the Random Forest Model is the best model to predict BIRTH_COMPLICATIONS. In the context of this question of determining presence of birth complications, False Positives can be detrimental for both mother and infant, as it would mean that the mother and infant could undergo additional procedures and internventions to prevent a birth complication that actually did not happen or not prepare for a birth complication that could actually heppen in the case of false negatives. This would mean that the patients could be faced with unjustified treatments and increase in hospital charges that were unnecssary. Since the overall performance between Random Forest and Decision Tree were very similar (65.7% for Random Forest and 65.8% for Decision Tree), the best model to address this question on predicting birth complications would be the Random Forest Model.

Question 1: Conclusion & Discussion¶

Based on all the results and analysis, it seems that birth-related risks and complications can be reasonably classified based on the various pregnancy and birth related factors in the data. Among the 3 models expored, it seems that random forest was the best model to use when accounting for preicison, recall, as well as False Positive and Negative rates to prevent over-treatment or under-treatment for mothers who may undergo birth complications. From the feature importance analysis of Random Forests and Decision Trees, birth weight had a direct relationship and was the major or only determinig factor in identifying birth complications. As a result, it can be said that birth-related risks and complications can be reasonable classified with birth weight being the determing factor.

In [37]:
#Use random undersampler to deal with imbalance in the data

#generate sampler using 50%-50% ratio for majority and minority classes
rus = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy=1.0) 

#resampling X, y
X, y = rus.fit_resample(X, y)

#split resampled X and y into train and test set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X ,y, test_size=0.20, random_state=1)

<sklearn.metrics._plot.confusion_matrix.ConfusionMatrixDisplay at 0x23ae8e4d460>

Logistic Regression model has an accuracy of 60.4%, similar to Naive Bayes. The precision is 59% and 63% for Class 0 and 1 respectively. The precision is better as compared to KNN but lower for Class 1 as compared to Naive Bayes.

Question 2: Conclusion & Discussion¶

To predict low birth in children, I used three classification models; KNN, Naive Bayes, and Logistic Regression. The KNN model gives the lowest accuracy. In terms of precision, the Naive Bayes model has the highest precision for both classes. Using an ROC curve, we can see that Naive Bayes and Logistic Regression perform better overall.

In light of the analysis above, we see that the best model has an accuracy of 71% and a precision of 70% and 80% for Class 0 (i.e. the child does not have a low birth weight) and Class 1 (i.e. the child has a low birth weight) respectively. Therefore, we cannot accurately predict low birth in children using the predictors available in the dataset.

Kmodes¶

k MODES uses the dissimilarities(total mismatches) between the data points. The lesser the dissimilarities the more similar our data points are. It uses Modes instead of means.

Question 3: Conclusion & Discussion¶

We began our study to see if we could uncover trends in each of the clusters we created, and we can plainly see that those mothers that did not have any birth complications, diabetes during their pregnancy or gestation period and who did not smoke during their pregnancy had healthy babies. On the other hand mothers who had birth complications, diabetes during their pregnancy or gestation period and reported smoking during their pregnancy, had babies with low birth and unfortunately some of the babies could not survive.

5) Future Work¶

Going forward, further addition of various pregnancy and birth factors, such as the mother's dietary habits, kinds of prenatal care, and other social determinants of health, will likely result in better preformances. The current features in the data only have very limited social factors like residence type, marital status, and age, and even more limited prenatal information like smoking and diabetes. More information on these topics such as dietary habits, mother's previous health like blood pressure, past diseases and drug intake, will further help determine the risks of birth just as birth weight has in this analysis. In addition, including data points beyond those from the state of Indiana as well as inclusion of other data points in this full dataset will certainly change the outcome of the model. Thus, future work should consider more data at the state level with more information on prenatal care, social and health factors of the model. Lastly, future work should also look into better methods of dealing with imbalanced data besides just simply sampling the data as a 50-50 ratio by accounting for location, year, and type of features included in the data for a more detailed analysis and prediction on birth complications.
